Let's begin by finding the derivative of the first equation with respect to x. This will help us to find the slope of the tangent line at any point on the parabola i.e.</think>
\begin{align*}
y =& x^2 + 15x + 32\\
\frac{dy}{dx} =& 2x + 15.
\end{align*}
<answer>At the point of tangency, the slope of the tangent line to both parabolas will be the same. Hence, we can equate the derivatives of the two parabolas and solve for x.</answer>

solution:
Let $P$ and $Q$ be the the intersection points of the two parabolas.  Then by definition of the parabola, the distance from $P$ to their common focus $F$ is equal to the distance from $P$ to the $x$-axis.  Also, the distance between $P$ to $F$ is equal to $P$ to the $y$-axis.  This means $P$ is equidistant to both the $x$-axis and $y$-axis, so $P$ must lie on the line $y = -x.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.15 cm);

pair F, P, Q;

real parab (real x) {
  return(-(x^2 - 6*x + 793)/56);
}

real upperparab(real x) {
  return(sqrt(3)*sqrt(2*x - 3) - 28);
}

real lowerparab(real x) {
  return(-sqrt(3)*sqrt(2*x - 3) - 28);
}

F = (3,-28);
P = (18.0385,-18.0385);
Q = (43.9615,-43.9615);

draw((-10,0)--(50,0));
draw((0,-50)--(0,10));
draw(graph(parab,-10,47),red);
draw(graph(upperparab,3/2,50),blue);
draw(graph(lowerparab,3/2,50),blue);
draw(F--P--(P.x,0));
draw(P--(0,P.y));
draw(F--Q--(Q.x,0));
draw(Q--(0,Q.y));
draw((-10,10)--(50,-50),dashed);

label("$F$", F, NW, UnFill);
label("$P$", P, NE, UnFill);
label("$Q$", Q, NE, UnFill);

dot(F);
